Chongqing’s secondary vocational schools are piloting a modern apprenticeship system, where students become quasi-employees of the companies upon enrollment – Xinhua News Agency
Yesterday, journalists learned from the Municipal Education Commission that starting this year, our city will pilot a “modern apprenticeship system” for talent cultivation in 60 secondary vocational schools. Students participating in this pilot program will have both the status of apprentices and, after being admitted, will be pre-registered as employees of the participating enterprises.
The Municipal Education Commission has requested the standardization of the enrollment and admission processes for secondary vocational schools, as well as the procedures for employers to hire workers. It is necessary to clarify the dual identities of apprentices: they are both students at secondary vocational schools and prospective employees of enterprises. In accordance with the principle of mutual selection, apprentices, schools, and enterprises should sign tripartite agreements. For apprentices who have reached the age of 16 but not yet 18, agreements must be signed by the apprentice, the guardian, the school, and the enterprise to define the rights and responsibilities of all parties, as well as the specific
Pilot schools are encouraged to adopt modern apprenticeship models and collaborate with enterprises to provide pre-employment training and retraining for employees.
Pilot schools need to reform the model of talent cultivation.
Schools and enterprises jointly design talent training programs, establish professional teaching standards, curriculum standards, job-related standards, standards for enterprise mentors, quality monitoring standards, as well as corresponding implementation plans.
The pilot program is designed to last for one academic cycle. The duration of students’ internships at companies is determined according to the professional training programs, with the typical internship period being six months.
In corporate practices, a team-based management model should be implemented. Depending on the characteristics of different professions, one master can guide 2 to 5 apprentices, forming learning groups to ensure that students acquire the necessary skills for each training position proficiently.
According to the plan, from 2016 to August 2019, our city identified 60 pilot projects for the modern apprenticeship system at the municipal level in three batches. Each pilot project involved around 50 participants, resulting in the training of approximately 3,000 students (apprentices) in total.
Following the principle of piloting first and then implementing, and progressing gradually from point to area, efforts should be made to establish a long-term mechanism for joint enrollment, joint training, and integrated education between schools and enterprises. This will effectively enhance students' job-related skills, increase their employment rate in relevant fields, and improve the quality of their employment.
