Educational Commentary: What is needed to rescue abducted children?
If we draw an analogy with the famous public service advertisement slogan “No buying, no selling; no killing,” then in an environment where there is no demand for child kidnapping, through collective prevention and public opposition to such crimes, trafficking activities would become unprofitable, high-risk, and costly. As a result, such crimes would not occur so frequently.
Recently, an emergency information release platform for missing children, developed by the Anti-Trafficking Office of the Criminal Investigation Bureau of the Ministry of Public Security, was launched.
This is an internet information platform established to create an authoritative channel for releasing information about missing children and to help in the timely recovery of abducted children.
Hearing that the app is called “Reunion,” it immediately feels very warm and comforting.
The new technological methods are not only named in a “literary” and emotionally rich way, but also make proper use of information technology; they are practical and effective.
The primary goal of anti-trafficking law enforcement is to recover the abducted children and ensure their personal safety and freedom.
Only afterwards comes the trial and punishment of the suspect.
The significance of criminal punishment can be discussed in various aspects, ranging from individual punishment and social prevention to legal education. There are many important concepts that can be mentioned in this context.
However, before the trafficking case is solved, priority should be given to ensuring the personal safety of the victims.
We need to prioritize matters based on their urgency. Under the pressing goal of “searching for and rescuing,” topics that are highly controversial and have different opinions, such as whether child trafficking should always be punishable by death, can be put aside for more cautious discussion. However, the rescue of abducted children cannot wait.
Based on the experience in investigating such cases, human traffickers tend to move away from the crime scene as quickly as possible after they have achieved their goal.
With every minute wasted in the search and rescue operation, the child may move further away from their parents, and the difficulty of solving the case increases accordingly.
In this situation, taking an effective approach such as using a platform like “Reunion” that directly helps in solving the case and finding the child is indeed a pragmatic move.
After all, "combating trafficking" is a major task that requires the entire legal system to be put in operation in order to be effectively carried out.
To combat crime and protect the rights of children and parents, it is necessary to implement a comprehensive approach that encompasses the improvement of legislation, the provision of judicial safeguards, and the meticulous enforcement of laws. All these aspects must be guided by the principle of caring for the vulnerable and protecting the young.
Furthermore, the prevention of child trafficking can be improved even more, from the family level to society as a whole.
For example, in a common scenario, a family of three is resting at the train station. The parents are fast asleep, and when they wake up, they realize that their child is missing.
You can’t expect a two-year-old child to have sufficient self-protection skills, but as the parent of such a young child, you should at least have a decent level of awareness about how to protect them.
It is the most basic measure to prevent children from being abducted: either parents take turns resting, or the children are placed in a safe and secure environment under protection.
From another perspective of the police’s efforts to combat trafficking crimes, the side that purchases the abducted children should also be addressed and punished.
A single illegal act is often just one link in a much longer chain of events.
According to the provisions of our country’s Criminal Law, the minimum penalty for the crime of trafficking in children is 5 years of imprisonment; in cases where the circumstances are particularly serious, the penalty can be death, accompanied by the confiscation of property.
With a high threshold for prosecution and severe maximum penalties, the crime of trafficking children clearly falls under the category of offenses that are subject to more stringent punishment, in line with the general trend towards mitigating the severity of criminal penalties.
Yet, to this day, a considerable number of cases of abduction and trafficking still occur every year.
It is evident that some people have outdated views on raising children and a weak sense of legal awareness.
The legal education for this group of people should be provided in a concurrent manner.
To effectively control the crime of trafficking, we cannot rely solely on strict law enforcement by the authorities.
If the “market” for child trafficking is widespread, and traffickers are driven by greed and constantly innovate their methods of trafficking, leading to a sort of “battle of wits” with law enforcement authorities, then efforts to combat child trafficking are bound to become inefficient and ineffective.
Therefore, breaking down outdated concepts and promoting legal knowledge can also help to effectively eradicate the crimes of child trafficking and purchase.
Yang Haodong delivered a speech on the spirit of the Sixth Plenary Session of the 19th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China and the Provincial Party Congress at Malanshan.
Draw strength for progress from the century-long struggle of the party
Hunan Daily, December 10th (All-media reporter: Gong Baiwei) According to the unified arrangements of the Provincial Party Committee, on the morning of December 10th, Yang Haodong, a member of the Standing Committee of the Provincial Party Committee and the head of the Provincial Party Committee’s Publicity Department, delivered an interactive lecture at the Malanshan Video and Cultural Innovation Park. The lecture focused on thoroughly studying and implementing the spirit of the Sixth Plenary Session of the 19th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China, as well as the important speeches, instructions, and directives of General Secretary
Yang Haodong explained the core essence and practical requirements of the plenary session's spirit in a clear, comprehensive, and systematic manner from three aspects: ideals and beliefs as well as the original mission; self-revolution and the role of the party as a youthful force; and the party's leadership and theories. He did so by combining his own insights and personal experiences.
He pointed out that it is necessary to study the spirit of the plenary session in conjunction with General Secretary Xi Jinping’s important speeches, instructions, and directives regarding Hunan, as well as the spirit of the provincial party congress. By integrating these elements, we can enhance our ideological, political, and practical awareness of defending the “two establishments” and achieving the “two upholds,” and resolutely move forward in the direction guided by General Secretary Xi Jinping.
