What was the biggest hit in 2021?
There’s no doubt it’s the Tokyo Olympics.
Do you think only Olympic athletes can win awards?
Some time ago, an article titled “Look! Project Managers Can Compete in Olympic Events for Gold Medals” became very popular. It mentioned that project managers are definitely in a position to take the lead in many projects, with no one being able to match them: carrying heavy loads, traveling on business, staying up late are all part of their daily routine, and stepping in to fix problems, taking the blame, and making apologies are also second nature to them.
An article that seems like a joke or a teasing piece of writing actually reveals the daily hardships faced by project managers, reflecting the sense of powerlessness in the current approach to project management.
And the personnel engaged in project management are also gradually choosing to take certain actions in order to get out of the difficulties they face at work.
Judging from the increasing number of applicants for the PMP (Project Management Professional) certification each year, it is evident that more and more professionals in the field of project management are improving their skills through learning.
According to the “China Project Management: Twenty Years of Development Report (1999-2019)”, as of September 2019, the total number of people who had registered for the PMP® exam nationwide was nearly 600,000, approximately 420,000 of them obtained the PMP® certification, and around 300,000 held valid certifications. This represents 31.2% of the total number of PMP® certifications globally.
In the past 10 years, the number of PMP (Project Management Professional) certifications has been increasing year by year. This indicates that more and more project managers are realizing that relying solely on traditional methods and past “experiences” is no longer effective. The rapidly changing work environment teaches us that we must learn from the achievements of scientific pioneers and build upon their knowledge to find new ways forward.
However, does obtaining the PMP certification guarantee that project management work will proceed smoothly without any obstacles?
Many beginners in project management say that by taking courses related to PMP/IPMP, they can systematically learn about the ten areas and five process groups of project management. However, when it comes to actually carrying out project management tasks, they still find themselves completely confused.
Many project managers often report the following issues: - A lack of proper understanding of project management principles; relying solely on personal experience, while possessing only theoretical knowledge without knowing how to apply it in practice. - The absence of a systematic project management process and supporting mechanisms, making it difficult to implement effective methods in work. As a result, project estimates are inaccurate, control is poor, and projects are constantly delayed. - Unclear division of responsibilities among team members, and those with more experience don’t know how to effectively manage new situations. - Inefficient cross-departmental communication, which hinders the progress of projects.
Therefore, having focused on product innovation and research and development (R&D) management for over a decade, Zhongtian Huaxia Consulting has helped numerous outstanding companies cultivate a large number of key R&D talents such as product managers and project managers. The company has also received honors such as “Demonstration Base for the Training of R&D Management Talents in Chinese Enterprises.” Now, Zhongtian Huaxia Consulting is bringing the online course “Special Training Camp for R&D Project Managers” to you.
“R&D Project Manager Training Camp” Online Course: This is an online, fragmented learning approach that combines practical cases, tools, and methods from numerous R&D-oriented companies to help you acquire the essential knowledge and standard procedures required for project management, paving your way towards advanced skills in project management.
This is also an opportunity for companies to promote the training of project managers at a lower cost and with less investment, thereby achieving more efficient operational results.
Words alone don’t carry much weight; it’s better to see what other students have to say about this course. This course is not only developed by an expert team from Zhongtian Huaxia (formerly part of Huawei’s R&D management team) but also incorporates internationally advanced project management methodologies and real business scenarios from numerous well-known companies, ensuring that the content is explained in a clear and professional manner.
It will also provide scientific and practical management tools and methods, as well as a wealth of template forms, to help participants apply what they have learned to their actual work after the course.
