On the eve of China’s “Double Twelve” shopping festival, Joyoung advocated for rational consumption among consumers – Economic Observation Network, a professional financial news website
This year, during the “Double Eleven” shopping festival, the total amount of transactions in online payment services across the country reached 1.77 trillion yuan, setting a new record compared to previous years.
The diverse range of promotional red envelopes, along with the eye-catching live-streaming sales events, have once again allowed consumers to feel that they are getting a great deal. On one hand, this surge in consumption highlights the growing purchasing power of the nation’s citizens; on the other hand, it also forces us to take a more cautious look at the impact of consumerism on society and the contemporary mainstream consumer group.
On the eve of “Double Twelve,” Credit Suisse Consumer Finance Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as “Credit Suisse”) issued a call for rational consumption, reminding users, especially young people, to develop good consumption awareness and habits, and to reject blind and excessive spending.
According to the results of the “Consumer Financial Literacy Survey and Analysis Report” released by the People’s Bank of China this year, the national consumer financial literacy index has reached 66.81, an increase of 2.04 compared to 2019.
Overall, the residents of our country perform well in terms of financial consumption. However, there are significant differences in various aspects of financial behavior and skills, indicating a need for further improvement in basic financial knowledge.
The levels of financial literacy among the elderly and teenagers are relatively low, and these two groups will continue to be a focus of financial education efforts. According to the “China Youth Debt Situation Report” released by Nielsen and the “2019-2020 China Youth Consumption Report” published by CCTV Finance, the younger generation possesses significant consumer potential. Credit consumption has become an important driver of consumption upgrading; 86.6% of young people use credit products, and nearly half of them have no accumulated debt. Although the overall trend among the youth is one of rational consumption, which contrasts with the label of “excessive
As a licensed consumer finance institution, Credit Suisse has always been committed to helping people build a happy life through high-quality and considerate services. It promotes the establishment of healthy and correct consumption habits among consumers and actively responds to regulatory requirements by taking practical actions to enhance the rational consumption awareness of consumers, especially the younger generation.
Over the past few years, Credit Suisse has continuously carried out comprehensive and diverse financial education initiatives targeting young people, including college students. By collaborating with top domestic universities and organizing innovative practice competitions, the company has subtly guided the consumption needs of this demographic, helping them develop a rational approach to spending and plan their financial needs effectively, thereby contributing to the accumulation of personal wealth.
As Double Twelve approaches, Joyoung reminds all consumers to develop a reasonable sense of spending and a correct attitude towards money. It encourages them to resist impulsive and excessive consumption, and to avoid misconceptions regarding consumer loans, in order to prevent any negative impact on their personal credit records or future financial well-being.
When making purchases, it is essential to plan in advance, spend within your means, and repay the loans on time.
If the payment is overdue, the overdue record will be included in the individual’s credit report, which may have negative consequences on future financial activities such as buying a car or a house.
At the same time, when enjoying financial products and services, it is important to choose reputable institutions and channels, and to verify whether the relevant organizations have the necessary qualifications to operate.
In the future, Joyoung will, as always, rely on its mature and reliable consumer finance system as well as continuously updated financial products to provide consumers with services that better meet their needs and are more diversified. It will continue to help the public improve their financial knowledge, foster the concept of rational consumption and moderate borrowing, and become a trusted partner in consumer finance for life.
