As NFTs become increasingly popular, a new concept has emerged within the crypto community.
In 2021, a blockchain game called Axie Infinity had a huge impact in Southeast Asia. Some residents who lost their jobs due to the pandemic began to earn a stable income from playing this game.
“Axie Infinity” is a pet-raising game based on blockchain technology, which incorporates various gameplay elements including NFTs. It is currently the NFT project with the highest transaction volume, having surpassed $3 billion to date.
According to TokenTerminal data, Axie Infinity’s daily revenue exceeded $8.2 million, coming close to the revenue of “Honor of Kings”.
On August 6th of this year, Axie Infinity officially announced that it had exceeded 1 million daily active users.
The popularity of Axie Infinity has introduced a new “play-to-earn” model to a wider audience. With the help of blockchain and smart contracts, players are no longer just passive characters within the game. In addition to enjoying the gameplay and earning financial rewards, they can also participate in the governance of the game’s ecosystem.
This sense of agency is not granted by the game developers, but is ensured by blockchain technology.
After reading a news article about the stock price of a friend of mine, my main takeaway is regarding the choice of industries by companies for their investments. Firstly, companies should opt for industries with significant growth potential, having a market size of at least 100 billion yuan or more. Secondly, they should choose industries that are expected to show good future growth, particularly those that are likely to reach their peak growth in the next 3 to 5 years. Lastly, it’s important to select industries that receive support from government policies.
The width of the “track” refers to the market size; the length of the “track” indicates the stage of development the industry is in; whether the track is flat or rugged reflects the competitive landscape of the industry.
Cheer for the correct track!
For the new year, the first thing to do is to summarize 2021 and adjust the tactical plan for 2022.
The tactic lies in “doing the things right,” which means doing things properly or correctly.
The strategy lies in “doing the right thing,” which means doing what is morally or ethically correct.
Strategy is about determining the direction, while tactics are about implementing that direction. Above most tactical considerations, there is always room for strategic thinking.
For example, beyond simply thinking about how to increase the number of customers (tactical thinking), one can consider whether to deepen existing areas of expertise or expand into related fields (strategic thinking). Similarly, when focusing on improving customer retention rates (tactical thinking), one can think about how to boost the retention of core and high-value customers (strategic thinking). When aiming to enhance event participation (tactical thinking), one should consider setting appropriate key performance indicators (KPIs) to achieve the desired goals, such as increasing engagement among target customers, activating inactive high-value customers, or acquiring new customers more effectively. And when focusing on
Twelve years after its inception, Bitcoin celebrated several milestone events in 2021.
On September 7th, El Salvador, a small country in Central America, designated Bitcoin as its official currency. This marks the first time that Bitcoin has become the official currency of a country or region.
On October 12th, for the first time in eight years, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) approved ProShares to launch a Bitcoin ETF, which was listed on the New York Stock Exchange. This marks the entry of the first compliant Bitcoin futures ETF into the U.S. capital market, further expanding the opportunities for investors in cryptocurrencies.
From the perspective of the development of blockchain technology, Bitcoin is not the main protagonist.
On November 14, 2021, Bitcoin underwent a soft fork upgrade called “Taproot.” This upgrade enhanced the anonymity of transactions on the Bitcoin network and reduced the data burden associated with transactions by altering the data structure of the blocks themselves.
