If your feet go numb while soaking in a foot bath tub, could it be due to an electrical leak?
Choosing the right foot bath tub can have a significant positive effect on foot care and health. Today, the editor from Gome will provide answers to this question, hoping it will be helpful to our friends.
As people's awareness of health and wellness increases, foot bath tubs have become increasingly popular among consumers. A wide range of products with different prices is available on the market, ranging from just over a hundred yuan to several thousand yuan, providing consumers with a great deal of choice.
According to the available data, health-related household appliances such as foot baths are selling very well compared to traditional home appliances. However, there are no specific industry standards for foot baths, which poses certain safety risks.
“Soaking your feet in charged water is really too dangerous, isn’t it?”
Mr. Li told the reporters that recently he bought a foot bath for his father as a birthday gift. However, when his father used the foot bath, he felt numbness in the soles of his feet.
At first, Mr. Li thought it was the vibration function of the foot bath tub causing the problem. To his surprise, even after turning off the vibration function, his father still felt a tingling sensation in the soles of his feet.
Mr. Li tested it with a test pen, and to his surprise, the pen lit up. He then discovered that the water in the foot bath was actually electrically charged.
Later, he contacted the merchant, and the merchant’s attitude was fairly good. Although the foot bath tub was returned, Mr. Li still felt dissatisfied.
Because he found that there are no clear and detailed industry regulations regarding the currently popular foot bath tubs – with regard to the highest temperature settings, the target user groups, or the materials used to ensure safety.
However, in general, foot baths do not have any issues related to electrical charging. Nevertheless, it is possible that a small number of products may not have undergone strict quality control before leaving the factory.
Therefore, when purchasing, choose a split-type foot bath tub.
The separation of water and electricity poses no safety hazards at all.
At the same time, you can use a stylus to measure whatever you want.
The 13th Provincial Tea Expo has opened – Video Highlights – Hunan Daily Online – Huasheng Online
Hunan Daily, December 10th (Reporters from all media outlets: Zhang Shangwu, Hu Panpan; Correspondents: Liu Xiaoling; Photographer: Li Jian) This morning, the 13th Hunan Tea Industry Expo and the Xinhua Black Tea Promotion Event were held at the Hunan International Convention and Exhibition Center. The event aimed to showcase the tea industry, promote innovative tea technologies, foster tea culture, and accelerate the achievement of the goal of a tea industry worth 100 billion yuan.
Hou Shunli, Deputy Director of the Council of the All-China Federation of Supply and Marketing Cooperatives, and Ye Hongzhuan, Deputy Director of the Standing Committee of the Provincial People's Congress, attended the opening ceremony.
Professor Liu Zhonghua, an academician of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, made a prominent announcement at the opening ceremony: The origin of Huhong tea lies in Xinhua, and the rise of black tea has injected new momentum into the development of “Wucai Xiangcha” (a variety of Hunan tea).
In recent years, the Provincial Party Committee and the Provincial Government have provided strong support for the development of the tea industry, promoting the construction of a tea industry worth hundreds of billions of yuan. As a result, a development pattern characterized by “tea from three regions of Hunan, produced using four types of water, and coming in a variety of colors” has been established.
The tea industry within the province is increasing its efforts in innovation. Key tea varieties such as green tea, dark tea, and black tea are all making significant contributions. The main tea-producing areas are promoting the integration of tea production with tourism, which helps to increase the income of the many tea farmers.
The cycle of feng shui continues, and black tea is making a comeback once again.
Experts in the tea industry within the province state that by harvesting green tea, followed by black tea and dark tea, tea farmers can generate income throughout the year, and the value of tea plantations continues to rise steadily.
During the opening ceremony, provincial leaders awarded plaques to the fourth batch of enterprises authorized to use the “Hunan Black Tea” trademark, with Xinhua being honored as the “Source of Hu Red” (the name for Hunan Black Tea).
At the Xinhua Black Tea Exhibition Hall, a Fujian tea merchant took a liking to a high-mountain tea variety called “Bing Li Chun” and placed an order on the spot.
Wang Zhun, the secretary-general of the Provincial Tea Industry Association, said happily that current factors such as the pandemic are more or less affecting the tea market. However, judging from the situation at the Tea Expo, there were many highlights.
The Xinhua black tea, with its distinctive red hue, has infused new meaning into the culture of tea. It is highly popular and generates brisk trade, bringing a new spring to the Hunan tea industry.
