Metaphysics refers to the study of questions that cannot be answered directly through perception, by using rational reasoning and logic.
Metaphysics is a fundamental principle of philosophy that aims to explain the essential nature of existence and the world.
The Chinese translation “Xing Er Mao Xi” (Metaphysics) is derived from the phrase “Xing er shang wa ze wei zhi dao; xing er shang wa ze wei qi” (What lies above form is called the Dao; what lies below form is called the vessel”) from the “I Ching • Xi Ci Shang Zhuan.” This term was translated by the Japanese scholar Tetsusaburo Inoue during the Meiji era from the English word “metaphysic.”
Branches of metaphysics include ontology, natural theology, and their related issues.
Ontology is the study of “which nouns represent real entities in existence, and which nouns merely represent concepts.”
Metaphysical naturalism refers to the denial of the existence of God.
The theoretical foundation of this approach holds that all phenomena can be explained by concepts of natural causes, and it was proposed by philosophers who support science and the theory of evolution.
Methodological naturalism refers to an approach of research that avoids making any mention of God.
Metaphysical philosophy is the branch of philosophy that examines the nature of consciousness and its relationship to the physical body, particularly the brain.
Dualism and monism are the two main schools of thought that discuss the relationship between the “soul and the body.”
Epistemology is a branch of philosophy that explores the nature, origin, and scope of knowledge.
Ethics is the discipline that systematically considers and studies human moral life; in this context, morality is defined as all the codes of conduct that are recognized by a particular group of people or culture.
It is mainly divided into two categories: Metaethics (which abstractly studies the nature of ethical theories or criticism) and Normative Ethics (which evaluates various moral perspectives and provides guidelines for what constitutes right or wrong behavior).
It studies the types of moral codes that people should adhere to, applied ethics (the academic application of ethical theories to real-life situations, including bioethics and political ethics), and descriptive ethics (the collection of information about how people live and the drawing of conclusions based on observed patterns).
Its ethical examination does not begin with predetermined theories, but rather with the actual choices made by moral agents that are observed in reality. It takes into account all the moral factors that influenced those decisions and explores the ethical perspectives held by different social groups.
The history of ethics includes Greek and Roman ethics, as well as medieval Christian ethics.
Part One: The ethical thought of Humanism, represented by figures such as Valla and Montaigne.
Part Two: The ethical thoughts of the Reformation, represented by Calvin.
Part Three: The Ethics of Politics Representative figures include Machiavelli and others. Modern ethics: – 17th–18th centuries: British empiricist ethics (representatives: Hume, etc.) – 17th–18th centuries: Continental rationalist ethics (representatives: Spinoza, etc.) – 18th century: French Enlightenment ethics (representative: Voltaire, etc.) – 18th–19th centuries: German academic ethics (representatives: Kant and Hegel, etc.) – 18th–
Logic is the discipline that studies the “principles and standards of valid reasoning and proof.”
Logic usually consists of three parts: inductive reasoning, abductive reasoning, and deductive reasoning. It can be divided into formal logic and informal logic.
Aesthetics is a discipline that focuses on the study of the nature of beauty and its significance.
