Chinese and Saudi curators jointly organized the first Saudi Biennial of Contemporary Art – Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Riyadh, December 12 (Reporters Wang Haizhou, Hu Guan) The first Saudi Arabian Biennial of Contemporary Art—the Diriyah Biennial of Contemporary Art—officially opened to the public on the 11th at the JAX Art District in Diriyah, located in the northwest of Riyadh, the capital of Saudi Arabia. A total of 64 artists from Saudi Arabia, China, and other countries participated in the exhibition.
This biennial exhibition was co-organized by the Saudi Diriyah Biennial Foundation and the UCCA (Ullens Center for Contemporary Art) in China, with Tian Feiyu, the director of UCCA, serving as the artistic director.
According to the curatorial team, the theme of this biennial exhibition is “Crossing the River by Feeling the Stones,” which metaphorically represents the reform strategies adopted during periods of socio-economic transformation and also reflects the current state of development in Saudi society and culture.
The biennial exhibition covers an area of nearly 12,000 square meters, with exhibition halls spread across six interconnected buildings. It is presented in six sections: “Crossing the River by Touching the Stones,” “Inheriting as an Experiment,” “Marginal Thinking,” “Reaching the Public,” “A Beautiful New World,” and “On the Spirit of Art.”
Among them, the works of 27 Saudi artists account for more than 40% of the total exhibits in this show, covering various forms such as painting, installation art, and performance art. The works of 12 Chinese artists have also received much attention; some of these artists use recycled materials in innovative ways to create their artwork. For example, in “The Story Behind Series: Endless Mountains and Rivers” (2014), Xu Bing reconstructed a classic landscape painting using waste materials.
Buckley, the CEO of the Diriyah Biennial Foundation, stated that they hope this biennial will foster international dialogue, providing global audiences with the opportunity to learn about Saudi Arabia’s thriving cultural industry and creative communities, and enhancing mutual exchanges.
Tian Feiyu said: “The goal of the biennial is twofold: it aims to enable Saudi contemporary art to participate in the global dialogue, as well as to integrate Saudi audiences into the world of contemporary art.”
It is understood that a series of lectures will also be held during the opening week of the biennial. Artists, curators, and leading figures in the creative industries will discuss topics such as cross-cultural communication and the development of contemporary art.
