The main stream of the Yangtze River has achieved full coverage of green, integrated water-based service areas – Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Wuhan, December 11 (Reporter Wang Xian) The Fuling Water-based Green Comprehensive Service Area in Chongqing was completed and put into operation on the 10th as scheduled. This is the second water-based green comprehensive service area to be officially operational in the upper reaches of the Yangtze River, following the opening of the Luzhou Water-based Green Comprehensive Service Area in Sichuan Province on the 8th.
To date, the Water Green Comprehensive Service Area has covered the upper, middle, and lower reaches of the Yangtze River.
Qiu Jianhua, the deputy director of the Yangtze River Navigation Administration under the Ministry of Transport, explained that previously, provinces such as Hubei, Hunan, Jiangxi, Anhui, and Jiangsu had established and operated 10 green, integrated water-based service areas in the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River. These areas have been well received by the ship crew and have played a significant role in promoting the high-quality development of river transportation on the Yangtze River.
The full coverage of the aquatic green integrated service areas represents another milestone in the construction of green shipping on the Yangtze River. The capacity of the Yangtze River to handle ship-generated pollutants and provide shipping services has been significantly enhanced.
According to the information provided, the Water Green Comprehensive Service Area is an important facility designed to offer a full range of production and living services to a wide variety of ships and their crew members, helping to address their urgent, difficult, and pressing needs.
The two newly established and operational aquatic green comprehensive service areas in the upper reaches of the Yangtze River integrate residential services, production services, and government services. Centered around the theme of environmental protection and featuring ship maintenance and emergency rescue services, these areas enable ships to receive multiple services with just one docking. This will make the work of crew members who navigate the Yangtze River throughout the year more efficient and their lives more convenient.
Three American aircraft carriers have assembled in the vicinity of China. One of the most powerful weapons in the U.S. military’s arsenal made a rare visit to Guam. 17/01/2022, MultiDimension Pro-China media outlets are reporting on the latest developments in Sino-U.S. relations: The latest satellite images show that three American aircraft carriers are gathering near China. American media also reveal that one of the most powerful weapons in the U.S. Navy’s arsenal made a rare appearance in Guam, sending an important signal to both U.S. allies and adversaries in the Indo-Pacific region.
According to the Chinese think tank “South China Sea Strategic Situation Awareness Platform,” on January 9, satellites detected the U.S. aircraft carrier USS Carl Vinson in the vicinity of the Balabac Strait.
The Balabac Strait connects the South China Sea with the Sulu Sea and is a strategically important location on the first island chain of the Western Pacific Ocean.
The platform predicts that the USS Carl Vinson will be deployed to the South China Sea.
This is the first time that the aircraft carrier USS Carl Vinson has deployed F-35C fighter jets and CMV-22 Osprey amphibious vehicles.
In addition to the USS Carl Vinson, there is also the USS Abraham Lincoln, which set sail from the United States on January 3rd, and both are currently operating in the upper Pacific Ocean.
The USS Lincoln also deployed for the first time an F-35C carrier-based aircraft squadron, which is part of the 314th Fighter Attack Squadron of the United States Marine Corps.
In addition to the two aircraft carriers mentioned above, the U.S. Navy currently has another carrier deployed in the Asia-Pacific region: the USS Ronald Reagan, which is stationed in Yokosuka, Japan.
The aircraft carrier battle group also includes the missile cruiser USS Lake Champlain and the missile destroyer USS Stockdale, among others.
Three US aircraft carriers have assembled in the vicinity of China. The most powerful weapons among them made a rare visit to Guam. On January 17, 2022, the “South China Sea Strategic Situation Awareness Platform” released the latest satellite images showing three US aircraft carriers gathering in the area surrounding China.
(Weibo @South China Sea Strategic Situation Awareness) Three American aircraft carriers have assembled near China; the most powerful weapons in their arsenal made a rare visit to Guam. On January 17, 2022, the flight route of the US military’s CMV-22B amphibious aircraft was as follows.
(Weibo @SouthChinaSeaStrategicSituationAwareness) According to a report by CNN on January 17th, one of the most powerful weapons in the U.S. Navy’s arsenal made a rare visit to Guam over the weekend.
The Ohio-class nuclear submarine USS Nevada, equipped with 20 Trident ballistic missiles and dozens of nuclear warheads, arrived at the U.S. Navy base in Guam on Saturday, January 15th.
The three U.S. aircraft carriers have been deployed near China’s borders. The most powerful weapons on board these carriers made a rare visit to Guam. Analysts believe this is a signal sent to both allies and enemies in the increasingly tense situation in the Indo-Pacific region.
This is the first time a U.S. ballistic missile submarine has visited Guam since 2016, and it marks the second public visit to Guam since the 1980s.
The three U.S. aircraft carriers have been deployed near China’s borders. The most powerful weapons among them made a rare visit to Guam. In recent years, China has constructed a large number of military facilities in the South China Sea.
The image shows Yongshu Island in the South China Sea, which belongs to China.
(The South China Sea Research Forum) The US Navy stated in a release that the visit of the Ohio-class nuclear submarine USS Nevada to Guam enhanced cooperation between the United States and its allies in the region. It demonstrated the United States’ capabilities, flexibility, combat readiness, as well as its ongoing commitment to the security and stability of the Indo-Pacific area.
Ballistic missile submarines are commonly referred to as “Boomer submarines”.
The whereabouts of the 14 Thresher submarines in the U.S. Navy fleet are usually kept strictly confidential.
The secrecy surrounding ballistic missile submarines made the Thresher submarine “the most important survivability weapon in the nuclear triad.” This triad also includes ballistic missiles launched from silos on U.S. soil, as well as bombers such as the B-2 and B-52 that are capable of carrying nuclear payloads.
When talking with friends about Meta’s recent sharp decline of 26% and the loss of $251 billion in market value, Zuckerberg responded by saying that the company is facing “unprecedented competition.” What could be the reasons for this?
Meta (formerly Facebook) is essentially an advertising company, with its revenue primarily coming from advertisements. In today’s world, advertising companies that generate profits usually have their own channels for attracting traffic.
Facebook, Instagram, WhatsApp, and others—regardless of their specific functional purposes—are all traffic channels for Meta.
Not only that, but Meta is also the largest “advertising alliance.” Many apps integrate Meta’s advertising services, and it is through Meta’s advertising platform that these apps generate revenue.
But times have changed.
Firstly, due to the changes in Apple’s privacy policy, it has become much more difficult for Meta to obtain user data, which has affected the efficiency of its advertising efforts.
Apple’s current privacy policy is user-friendly and clearly informs users whether the app is allowed to access their information. The natural reaction of most people would certainly be to deny such access.
If Google manages to cause further damage in the future, the impact on Meta’s revenue will be even greater.
Secondly, the contribution of China to Meta’s past revenue growth has also diminished (the exact proportion of this factor is uncertain, but it was indeed significant).
Everyone generally knows that Meta does not have any operations in China, but this understanding is not entirely accurate.
Every year, Meta generates at least 10% of its revenue from China, with the majority of this revenue coming from Chinese companies that operate overseas.
Meta has several hundred employees in its office in Hong Kong, as well as several major agents on the Chinese mainland.
Chinese companies want to expand into overseas markets, and Meta is an advertising channel that they cannot bypass. Most of the money spent on these efforts goes to Meta.
Interestingly, ByteDance’s TT service is now one of Meta’s main competitors, yet Meta made a considerable amount of money from ByteDance in the previous two years.
Various domestic agencies are helping ByteDance with advertising on Meta, and Meta’s performance in the Greater China region is also very good.
I haven’t specifically looked into it recently, but it definitely can’t be any better than it was before.
The phase in which Chinese companies were spending large amounts of money overseas has passed.
Thirdly, the expansion of new traffic channels has not been successful.
Facebook is getting older and older; new platforms, including TT, are no longer under the control of Meta.
The biggest problem is not just the decline in income, but also the lack of expectations for growth.
The capital market doesn’t only focus on income; what’s more important is the outlook for the future.
It’s quite obvious that Meta’s expectations were not sufficient.
In order to tell a new story to the market, Zuckerberg talked about the “metaverse.”
The metaverse is indeed one of the potential directions for the future, but the process of realizing it takes a relatively long time. The developments in the past couple of years should not be sufficient to justify Meta’s current market value.
So, the next two years should be a relatively tough period for Meta.
Despite Facebook’s current success and annual revenues of $100 to $200 billion, it is actually in a state of significant crisis. Compared to other internet companies and high-tech firms, it does not possess any strong or effective protective mechanisms (or “moats”) to safeguard itself from potential threats.
Although several of his social media apps currently have high daily user counts and are considered mainstream platforms, such as Facebook and WhatsApp, Facebook doesn’t have much confidence in the face of TikTok’s rapid growth. The potential for disruption could happen in the blink of an eye.
The concept of the metaverse is something that seems promising yet remains out of reach, and there’s no chance of success in the short term. Therefore, Facebook is in a very dangerous position. This is also the fundamental reason why Zuckerberg keeps changing the company’s name and constantly searching for new areas of focus. However, I think his choices are wrong; they lead down a path with no return. The above are just some of my thoughts for your reference.
Article 17: The state implements a registration and practice management system for the qualifications of certified fire engineers.
Individuals who have obtained the qualification certificates for Level 1 or Level 2 Certified Fire Engineers can practice in the name of a Certified Fire Engineer at the corresponding level, through the registration process conducted by the relevant authorities.
Article 18: The Fire Bureau of the Ministry of Public Security is the authority responsible for the registration and approval of qualifications for Level 1 Certified Fire Engineers.
The fire protection agencies of the public security departments in provinces, autonomous regions, and municipalities directly under the Central Government are the authorities responsible for the registration and approval of candidates with the qualification of Level 2 Certified Fire Engineers. They also undertake the preliminary review process for the registration of candidates with the qualification of Level 1 Certified Fire Engineers.
Article 19: Individuals who have obtained the qualification certificates for Level 1 or Level 2 Certified Fire Engineers and wish to register must be employed by an approved fire technology service organization or a key unit for fire safety. They shall submit their registration application materials to the fire department of the public security authorities at the location of their employer (or, if the employer is a company, to the local industrial and commercial registration authority).
Article 20: Upon receiving the registration application materials from the applicant, the fire protection authorities of the provincial, autonomous regional, or municipal public security departments shall, if the materials are incomplete or do not comply with the statutory requirements, inform the applicant in person or within 5 working days of all the necessary corrections. Failure to provide such information within the prescribed time shall be deemed as acceptance of the application from the date the materials were received.
For both approved and rejected registration applications, a written certificate should be issued, bearing the official seal of the fire protection agency of the local public security department and the date of issuance.
Article 21: The fire protection agencies of the public security departments at the provincial, autonomous region, and municipal levels shall, within 20 working days from the date of receiving the registration application, complete the preliminary review of the application materials for the qualification of a Level 1 registered fire engineer in accordance with the prescribed conditions and procedures, as well as the approval process for the registration of a Level 2 registered fire engineer. They shall then submit the application materials for the Level 1 registered fire engineer qualification and the preliminary review findings to the Fire Protection Bureau of the Ministry of Public Security for final approval.
The Fire Department of the Ministry of Public Security shall make a decision on whether to approve the application within 20 working days from the date of receiving the application materials and preliminary review opinions submitted by the fire agencies of the provincial public security organs.
If a decision of approval cannot be made within the prescribed period, the applicant should be informed of the extended period and the reasons for the delay.
For decisions denying approval, the reasons must be stated in writing, and the applicant must be informed of their right to apply for administrative reconsideration or to initiate an administrative lawsuit in accordance with the law.
Article 22: The registration approval authority shall issue and deliver the registration certificate at the corresponding level within 10 working days from the date of making the approval decision.
Article 23: The validity period of each registration certificate is 3 years.
The registration certificate is a valid proof of practice for a registered fire engineer at the corresponding level and shall be kept and used by the registered fire engineer himself/herself.
Article 24: Applications for initial registration must be submitted within one year from the date of obtaining the qualification certificate for a Level 1 or Level 2 registered fire engineer.
When applying for initial registration after the deadline, the requirements for continuing education specified in these regulations must be met.
The specific procedures for registration management, such as initial registration, renewal of registration, change of registration, cancellation of registration, and refusal to grant registration, shall be stipulated separately by the Ministry of Public Security.
Article 25: Continuing education is a prerequisite for registered fire engineers to renew their registration, re-register, or complete the initial registration process after the expiration of the registration period.
During each valid registration period, fire engineers registered at all levels must complete the required continuing education as stipulated.
Article 26: The registration and approval authorities shall promptly announce to the public information related to the registration of certified fire engineers, establish a credit record for these professionals, and implement a credit management system for their practice activities.
Article 27: The registration authorities responsible for the certification of fire engineers at all levels shall strictly enforce the relevant provisions of the Administrative Licensing Law of the People's Republic of China.
That’s all for the exam information sharing for today. I hope it can be of some help to everyone.
Everyone must work hard to prepare for the exams and strive to pass the Fire Engineer certification as soon as possible!
